solution:
We look for the least number of years $n$ it takes for the savings to be greater than or equal to the costs. \begin{align*}
1200n&\ge10,000+650n\quad\Rightarrow\\
550n&\ge10,000\quad\Rightarrow\\
n&\ge\frac{10,000}{550}=18.\overline{18}
\end{align*}The smallest integer greater than $18.\overline{18}$ is 19, so it will take $\boxed{19}$ years to recuperate the costs.

First, we use the distributive property to expand the first two factors:

\begin{align*}
6(x+2)(x+3) &= (6\cdot x + 6 \cdot 2) (x+3)\\
&=(6x+12)(x+3)
\end{align*}We use the distributive property again by adding the product of $6x+12$ and $x$ to the product of $6x+12$ and 3:

\begin{align*}
(6x+12)(x+3) &= (6x+12) \cdot x +(6x+12) \cdot 3\\
&= x(6x+12) + 3(6x+12)
\end{align*}We use the distributive property again and combine like terms:

\begin{align*}
x(6x+12) + 3(6x+12) &= 6x^2 + 12x + 18x+ 36\\
&= \boxed{6x^2 + 30x + 36}
\end{align*}

We can rewrite $2007^3$ as the cube of a binomial: \begin{align*}
2007^3 &= (2\cdot 10^3 + 7)^3\\
&= \binom{3}{0} (2\cdot 10^3)^3 + \cdots + \binom{3}{3} 7^3
\end{align*}

Only the first and last term of the binomial expansion affect the values of $F$ and $L$. The first term is equal to $8\cdot 10^9$, so $F = 8$. The last term is equal to 343, so $L = 3$. Therefore, $F + L = \boxed{11}$.

